{"title_page": "Jeffrey Anderson (game designer)", "text_new": "{{short description|American video game designer and entrepreneur}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Jeffrey Anderson\n| image        = Jeff Anderson at NYME 2017.jpg\n| caption      = Jeffrey Anderson at NYME 2017\n| birth_name   = Jeffrey Anderson\n| birth_place  = [[Rockford, Illinois]], U.S.\n| residence    = [[Boston, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   = Executive Vice President, [[Game Show Network]] Games\n| years_active = 2013\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Josette Anderson |2019}} {{marriage|Susan Anderson (deceased) |1990}}\n| children     = 2\n}}\n\n'''Jeffrey Anderson''' is the [[Executive Vice President]] of Social Casino and Bingo at the [[Game Show Network]], working for Mark Feldman who was promoted to CEO in 2017.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/gsn-promotes-mark-feldman-ceo-1026513 \"GSN Promotes Mark Feldman to CEO\"] Retrieved January 2, 2018.</ref> He was formerly the SVP and GM over the Bingo Bash Studio, one the world's most profitable and successful social bingo games according to the CY16 annual report published by Eilers and Krejcik.<ref>[https://postmaster.bluematrix.com/Postmaster/EmailDocViewer.action?info=uTjFbTActy2yRsdhPN1WmsDFr%2B0JKc7WWc1zYm93%2FMXnvwRZhURO0zJ9DBLcE3QcYD6VimsPr0QUeRXDIwhu%2Frfip9dhx6LZPwNEPb%2BS1hhLDsoJmzkDf%2BLJ0m%2BF7zOeukvIx7jNerOUZ8%2FikaqnOJ44kl3dJq1UZch9KVQgRQU%3D \"Social Casino Gaming Tracker - 4Q16 and CY16\"] Retrieved January 2, 2018.</ref> Prior to that, he served as the company's Chief Strategy Officer under [[David Goldhill]] where he was responsible for acquiring the makers of Bingo Bash<ref>[https://venturebeat.com/2014/02/25/bingo-gsn-buys-bash-gaming-for-an-estimated-160m-to-170m/ \"Bingo! GSN buys Bash Gaming for an estimated $160M to $170M\"] Retrieved January 2, 2018.</ref> and others. He joined the company in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://corp.gsn.com/press/releases/gsn-hires-jeff-anderson-senior-vice-president-strategic-planning-and-business-develop |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150628044058/http://corp.gsn.com/press/releases/gsn-hires-jeff-anderson-senior-vice-president-strategic-planning-and-business-develop |archive-date=June 28, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Previously, he was the [[Senior Vice President|SVP]] of [[Majesco Entertainment|Majesco Ent. Company]]. He joined the company in 2011.<ref>[http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/35074/Majesco_Expands_Social_Strategy_With_Quick_Hit_Acquisitions.php \"Majesco Expands Social Strategy With Quick Hit Acquisition\"] Retrieved April 13, 2020</ref> In his role, he oversaw Majesco's social and mobile business, including [[Quick Hit Football]], [[Cooking Mama]] and other titles.  Prior to joining Majesco, he was a CEO and President of Quick Hit Inc. and [[Turbine Inc]] where he raised $30 million from Tudor et al.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ctventures.com/news.asp?ArticleID=196 |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004214046/http://www.ctventures.com/news.asp?ArticleID=196 |archive-date=October 4, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Prior to that, he was the Executive in Charge of Production for [[Electronic Arts]], overseeing [[Ultima Online]].<ref>[https://www.mobygames.com/developer/sheet/view/developerId,26529/ \"Jeffrey Anderson Video Games Credits\"] Retrieved March 27, 2020</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJeffrey Anderson received an undergraduate degree from the [[University of Illinois]] where he was one in the top 3% of his graduating class.<ref>[https://digital.library.illinois.edu/items/af312ba0-13c4-0134-1d5f-0050569601ca-9#?c=0&m=0&s=0&cv=0&r=0&xywh=-1110%2C218%2C9092%2C3449 \"U. of I. Bronze Tablet 1989\"] Retrieved March 27, 2020</ref> He also has a [[Juris Doctor|JD]] from the [[University of Chicago]] where he served on the [[University of Chicago Law Review]].<ref>https://lawreview.uchicago.edu/sites/lawreview.uchicago.edu/files/uploads/About/Mastheads/v59.pdf</ref> After graduating, he went to work as an attorney at the law firm of Holleb & Coff in [[Chicago, Illinois]]. Feeling that the legal profession was not for him, he joined with Thomas Ptak and others to start [[Mission Studios]] (which was later sold to [[Take-Two]]). After that, he moved to [[Los Angeles]] and joined [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]'s consumer products division where he worked on various initiatives from [[Star Trek]] licensing to the [[Bubba Gump Shrimp Company]]. In 1998, [[Electronic Arts]] recruited him to join its [[Austin, Texas]] studio to oversee the [[Ultima Online]] franchise along with [[Raph Koster]] and [[Richard Garriott]]. Then, in 2001, [[Turbine Inc]] recruited him to be its President and CEO. The company had a software development agreement with [[Microsoft]] at the time to develop [[Asheron's Call 2]], but wanted to expand the business and become the largest independent [[MMORPG]] company in the world. Anderson successfully raised capital from [[Highland Capital Partners]] and [[Polaris Venture Partners]], and secured the rights to develop two new [[MMORPG]] games known as [[Dungeons & Dragons Online]] and [[The Lord of the Rings Online]]. After leaving Turbine in 2008 (which was subsequently sold to [[Warner Brothers]]<ref>[http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2010/04/warner-bros-acquires-turbine.html \"Warner Bros. acquires Turbine\"] Retrieved April 13, 2020</ref>), he founded [[Quick Hit]]. This new online gaming studio developed the world's first free-to-play [[National Football League]]-licensed online football game.<ref>[https://venturebeat.com/2010/06/10/quick-hit-scores-nfl-license-for-online-football-games/ \"Quick Hit Score NFL\"] Retrieved April 13, 2020</ref> The company raised capital from [[New Enterprise Associates]] before it was sold to Majesco in 2011. Two years after the sale, Anderson joined the [[Game Show Network]] as its CSO.\n\n==Awards==\n* ''[[Boston Globe]] 100 - Top Innovators in Massachusetts' <ref>[http://archive.boston.com/business/technology/innoeco/2011/05/globe_100_ceo_roundtable_the_e.html \"Globe 100 CEO\"] Retrieved April 13, 2020</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American video game designers]]\n[[Category:American game designers]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American video game designer and entrepreneur}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Jeffrey Anderson\n| image        = Jeff Anderson at NYME 2017.jpg\n| caption      = Jeffrey Anderson at NYME 2017\n| birth_name   = Jeffrey Anderson\n| birth_place  = [[Rockford, Illinois]], U.S.\n| residence    = [[Boston, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   = Executive Vice President, [[Game Show Network]] Games\n| years_active = 2013\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Josette Anderson |2019}} {{marriage|Susan Anderson (deceased) |1990}}\n| children     = 2\n}}\n\n'''Jeffrey Anderson''' is the [[Executive Vice President]] of Social Casino and Bingo at the [[Game Show Network]], working for Mark Feldman who was promoted to CEO in 2017.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/gsn-promotes-mark-feldman-ceo-1026513 \"GSN Promotes Mark Feldman to CEO\"] Retrieved January 2, 2018.</ref> He was formerly the SVP and GM over the Bingo Bash Studio, one the world's most profitable and successful social bingo games according to the CY16 annual report published by Eilers and Krejcik.<ref>[https://postmaster.bluematrix.com/Postmaster/EmailDocViewer.action?inf